# TYPOGRAPHY

Use:
- Inter
OR
- Geist

Typography sizes:
- Page title: 24px (use `text-2xl`) — prefer **font-semibold** or **font-medium**, never **extrabold/black** for tenant or platform UIs
- Section title: 20px (`text-xl font-semibold`)
- Card title: 16px (`text-base font-medium`)
- Body text: 14px
- Table text: 13px
- Labels: 12px — **font-medium**; avoid **all-caps + widest tracking** except rare NOC badges

Typography must be:
- highly readable
- clean
- enterprise-grade
- **low visual weight** (operational calm): default to `font-normal`/`font-medium` for data; reserve `font-semibold` for page titles and primary actions only

**Board / investor materials:** If `docs/Rules/TowerOS_Board_Presentation.pdf` (or `Rules/TowerOS_Board_Presentation.pdf`) is added to the workspace, keep module names, grouping (Infrastructure vs Governance), and hierarchy aligned with that document.

---

# LAYOUT RULES

Use:
- left sidebar
- top header
- workspace layout
- responsive design
- collapsible navigation

Navigation hierarchy:
1. Module
2. Feature
3. Action

Always preserve:
- filters
- search
- map state
- active tabs

---

# COMPONENT RULES

Cards:
- rounded-xl
- soft shadows
- clean padding
- minimal borders

Tables:
- sticky headers
- column filters
- bulk actions
- export support
- pagination
- search
- responsive

Forms:
- large readable inputs
- clear labels
- inline validation
- grouped sections
- keyboard-friendly

Buttons:
- clean
- medium height
- clear hover states
- icon support

Modals:
- minimal
- prefer side drawers when possible

---

# DASHBOARD RULES

Dashboards must focus on:
- actionable data
- alerts
- tasks
- pending approvals
- SLA risks
- operational visibility

Avoid:
- excessive charts
- clutter
- unnecessary widgets

---

# MAP DESIGN

Maps are core UI elements.

Use:
- dark operational maps
- clean markers
- clustered points
- color-coded alarms
- overlay layers

Maps should feel like:
- network operation centers
- telecom monitoring systems

---

# UX RULES

Critical workflows:
- maximum 3 clicks

Prefer:
- inline actions
- side panels
- command palette
- smart search

Avoid:
- too many popups
- deep nested menus
- cluttered screens

---

# MOBILE UX

Field engineer screens must prioritize:
- large touch targets
- offline support
- fast forms
- camera uploads
- QR scanning
- GPS workflows

---

# ANIMATION RULES

Use minimal animations.

Allowed:
- subtle hover
- fade transitions
- loading skeletons

Avoid:
- bouncing
- excessive motion
- distracting transitions

---

# DESIGN QUALITY

All generated UI must:
- feel enterprise-grade
- be production-ready
- maintain consistency
- support scalability
- support accessibility
- support dark/light themes
- support large datasets
- support operational users

Always think like a senior enterprise UX architect.